abstract: GREENWICH, Conn., Oct. 31. -- Viola Allen, the actress, was robbed here a few days ago of a diamond ring valued at $1,000 white visiting her brother, Charles W. Allen. The thief afterward became repentant, and, returning, left a note giving the address where the ring could be recovered, and inclosing three $100 bills, the amount for which it had been pawned.

abstract: DOYLESTOWN, Penn., Oct. 31. -- It has been learned that Judge Edward M. Paxson, who died at Bycot, Bucks County, on Oct. 12, left part of his $3,000,000 fortune for the endowment of a college of agriculture. The college is to be opened to boys between 12 and 18 years old, and a regular course of study is to be arranged so that mental equipment as well as soil-tilling experience will be given.

abstract: I was very much disappointed last Saturday in the review given of Prof. Paul Monroe's interesting book on the "History of Education." abstract: NEWBURG, Nov. 5. -- A vigilant engineer saved the Western Express on the West Shore Railroad from a bad wreck last night six miles north of this city. abstract: WARSAW, Nov. 5. -- Great patriotic demonstrations were held in the streets to-day by crowds estimated as numbering 200,000. Processions, headed by clergy and singing "God Save Poland," paraded the principal streets, which were elaborately decorated. The balconies and windows of the houses were filled with spectators. Citizen guards kept exemplary order, and the military massed in the side streets had no occasion to interfere.

abstract: MOUNT VERNON, N.Y., Nov. 21. -- The meeting of the Board of Aldermen here to-night bordered on a riot. During the proceedings Mayor Brush called on the police to arrest Alderman Clark, one of two Republican leaders of the board.
